entry.title: HOW TO CREATE A *_DATA SCIENCE - MACHINE LEARNING - DEEP LEARNING BLOG_* using Python, Jupyter Notebooks, Pelican, and Bootstrap
entry.summary:
For many who aspire to learn the craft of machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL), python is language of choice. With Python's outstanding libraries for ML such as Scikit-learn and keras (friendly front-end for Google's TensorFlow) for DL and the ease of using Jupyter Notebooks in your browser to run models makes Python an easy choice. But what about creating ML/DL blogs and websites with links to GibHut repositories to showcase your analyses and code? After all, R has RStudio and Shiny which make these task very simple and produce beautiful websites and apps. No so much for Pythonista data scientists. There are tools like Django and Flask but they are not simple or quick like R Shiny and most data scientists want to spend their time analyzing data rather than learning new tools for web design.

Enter Pelican. Designed to transform Markdown documents like Jupyter Notebooks into HTML that is ready to host on a web server like github.io via GitHub Pages. Not as simple as R Shiny but that difficult either.

So how do blogs produced by Pelican look? Okay but quite the same as R Shiny. Why?

The default theme used by Pelican.

While R Shiny uses Twitter Bootstrap as it's default theme, Pelican does not. Fortunately this can be changed with some setup work and the purpose of this post to make it easier for a data scientist to accomplish this. What follows is a complete 'recipe' for integrating bootstrap into your Pelican blog for a very professional looking site. Since there are many steps involved, the rest of this post will be in outline form to create a 'cheatsheet' for your reference.

For more background on using Pelican to create a data scinece blog, see this excellent post from dataquest.io https://www.dataquest.io/blog/how-to-setup-a-data-science-blog/

QUICKSTART USING MARKDOWN

A. INSTALL AND ACTIVATE A VIRTUALENV FOR PELICAN BLOG SITE - pip install virtualenv - virtualenv ~/virtualenvs/pelican - cd ~/virtualenvs/pelican - . bin/activate

B. NEXT INSTALL PELICAN & MARKDOWN IN THE VIRTUALENV - (pelican) $ pip install pelican - (pelican) $ pip install Markdown

C. NOW RUN PELICAN-QUICKSTART FROM YOUR PELICAN VIRTUALENV AND INSTALL REQUIREMENTS - (pelican) $ pelican-quickstart - (pelican) $ answer questions: defaults except: URL prefix: N, TIMEZONE: America/New_York - (pelican) $ pip install -r requirements.txt

D. CREATE .md FILE IN CONTENT WITH BLOG

E. START DEVELOPMENT WEB SERVER TO VIEW WEBSITE IN BROWSER - (pelican) $ make devserver - IN BROWSER OPEN localhost:8000

F. TO STOP LOCALHOST SERVER - (pelican) $ ./develop_server.sh stop

HOW TO CONVERT A Jupyter Notebook INTO A BLOG POST

G. INSTALL JUPYTER PLUGIN AS GIT SUBMODULE - (pelican) $ git init - (pelican) $ mkdir plugins - (pelican) $ git submodule add git://github.com/danielfrg/pelican-ipynb.git plugins/ipynb

H. MODIFY pelicanconf.py TO INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING LINES: - MARKUP = ('md', 'ipynb')

  • PLUGIN_PATHS = ['./plugins']
  • PLUGINS = ['ipynb.markup']

I. COPY .ipynb INTO content FOLDER CREATED BY pelican-quickstart

J. NOW CREATE A FILE WITH THE MARKDOWN META DATA FOR THE POST IN CONTENT DIR USING THE SAME NAME AS .ipynb BUT HAS THE EXTENTION .ipynb-meta

Title: MY NEW BLOG POST Slug: new-post FILENAME Date: 2017-12-22 17:30 DATE POSTED Category: posts Tags: python 'data science' 'machine learning' 'deep learning' author: Brian Griner, PhD Summary: BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF CONTENT OF NEW POST

K. GENERATE HTML INTO OUTPUT DIR FROM MARKDOWN FILES IN CONTENT DIR - (pelican) $ cd .. (OR ~/virtualenv/pelican) - (pelican) $ pelican content TO GERNERATE HTML IN output folder

L. START PELICAN WEBSERVER AND REVIEW BLOG IN BROWSER: - (pelican) $ cd output - (pelican) $ python -m pelican.server - (pelican) $ localhost:8000 IN BROWSER TO VIEW POST

M. CREATE A STATIC HOME PAGE USING MARKDOWN - (pelican) $ mkdir content/pages (ALSO content/posts TO STORE POSTS) - USE OVERRIDE FEATURE IN MARKDOWN METADATA FILE:

Title: Data Science & Learning Systems LLC URL: save_as: index.html

Thank you for visiting my blog ...

USE PELICAN-THEMES TO INSTALL BOOTSTRAP2 THEME

N. INSTALL PELICAN THEMES FROM GITHUB SITE - (pelican) $ git clone --recursive https://github.com/getpelican/pelican-themes ~/pelican-themes

O. RUN pelican-themes TO LIST INSTALLED THEMES, INSTALL NEW OR REMOVE EXISTING THEMES - (pelican) $ pelican-themes -v -l TO LIST INSTALLED THEMES - (pelican) $ pelican-themes --install

P. ADD THEME VARIABLE TO PELICANCONF.PY WITH THEME NAME - THEME = "bootstrap2"

Q. RUN PELICAN WITH -t bootstrap2 - (pelican) $ pelican content -s pelicanconf.py -t bootstrap2

R. CHANGE TO OUTPUT DIR, START PELICAN WEBSERVER, AND VIEW SITE IN BROWSER - cd output - python -m pelican.server - OPEN localhost:8000 IN BROWSER

NOW ADD GITHUB PAGES AS REMOTE TO LOCAL REPO

S. STOP WEBSERVER IN LOCALHOST - deactivate (./develop_server.sh stop?)

T. COMMIT FILES TO GITHUB - git checkout -b dev CREATE AND SWITCH TO BRANCH dev - ghp-import output -b master TO IMPORT ALL FILES FROM output TO master - git push origin master TO PUSH CONTENT TO GITHUB

U. CHECK briangriner.github.io FOR NEW BLOG POST!

<p>Source: <a href="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Pima_Indian_woman_winnowing_beans_over_her_head_onto_a_mat_on_the_ground%2C_Gila_River_Reservation%28%3F%29%2C_ca.1902_%28CHS-771%29.jpg/797px-Pima_Indian_woman_winnowing_beans_over_her_head_onto_a_mat_on_the_ground%2C_Gila_River_Reservation%28%3F%29%2C_ca.1902_%28CHS-771%29.jpg">https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/24/Pima_Indian_woman_winnowing_beans_over_her_head_onto_a_mat_on_the_ground%2C_Gila_River_Reservation%28%3F%29%2C_ca.1902_%28CHS-771%29.jpg/797px-Pima_Indian_woman_winnowing_beans_over_her_head_onto_a_mat_on_the_ground%2C_Gila_River_Reservation%28%3F%29%2C_ca.1902_%28CHS-771%29.jpg</a></p>

<h2 id="Motivation">Motivation<a class="anchor-link" href="#Motivation">¶</a></h2><p>The Pima Indians in Arizona have been part of an ongoing study since 1965 by the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases due to the high incidence of diabetes. Many research studies have been done on this population over the years. A theme in this body of research is the ongoing debate around "nature vs. nuture" in determining the cause of diabetes onset and whether it can be prevented through behavioral changes. Links to example references are provided below.</p>
<p>Nature references
<a href="http://diabetes.diabetesjournals.org/content/53/5/1181">http://diabetes.diabetesjournals.org/content/53/5/1181</a></p>
<p>Nuture references
<a href="http://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/29/8/1866.full">http://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/29/8/1866.full</a></p>
<p>Commentary from the Indian Country Media Network on 'causal factors'
<a href="https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/mexico-vs-arizona-pima-indians/">https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/mexico-vs-arizona-pima-indians/</a></p>
<p>Ongoing logitudinal study protocol (since 2006) - no results yet
<a href="https://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT00340132">https://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT00340132</a></p>
<p>In this post, we will analyzing the Pima Indians Diabetes dataset from the UCI ML repository to examine how different methodological approaches impact the insights obtained from this data and recommendations that follow.</p>
<p>Several examples of ML applications using this data can be found on Kaggle <a href="https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/pima-indians-diabetes-database">https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/pima-indians-diabetes-database</a>. Kaggle competitions are typically based on algorithm performance as do many of the ML examples on the site. While ML performance is an important element of ML, it is not usually the end goal. ML/DL is effective when used to analyze complex research problems where the underlying relationships between cause and effect are not well known. In the <em>Hacking Health</em> posts, I will be focusing on the potential benefits of using ML/DL to analyze real-word data on public health and other social issues.</p>
<h2 id="Overview">Overview<a class="anchor-link" href="#Overview">¶</a></h2><p>The Pima Indians Diabetes dataset can found in the UCI Machine Learning Repository and is widely used for teaching data science, machine learning (ML), and deep learning (DL) <a href="https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Pima+Indians+Diabetes">https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Pima+Indians+Diabetes</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Pima Indians Diabetes Data</strong></p>
<p>The data available on UCI ML repository was used in a study at Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine to test the performance of a neural network designed for predicting diabetes using a subset of attritubes on a subset of the study population. <a href="http://pubmedcentralcanada.ca/pmcc/articles/PMC2245318/pdf/procascamc00018-0276.pdf">http://pubmedcentralcanada.ca/pmcc/articles/PMC2245318/pdf/procascamc00018-0276.pdf</a></p>
<p><strong> The population defined by this subset of data are <em>women at least 18 yrs old of Pima Indian descent</em>.</strong></p>
<p>was collected for the purpose of primary research on diabetes to help identify risk factors for developing pre-diabetes in 1-5 years.</p>
<h1 id="Description-of-Data-(from-UCI-ML-site)">Description of Data (from UCI ML site)<a class="anchor-link" href="#Description-of-Data-(from-UCI-ML-site)">¶</a></h1><p><strong>Abstract:</strong> From National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases; Includes cost data (donated by Peter Turney)</p>
<p><strong>Data Set Characteristics:</strong> <em>Multivariate</em>
<strong>Number of Instances:</strong> <em>768</em>
<strong>Area:</strong> <em>Life</em>
<strong>Attribute Characteristics:</strong> <em>Integer, Real</em>
<strong>Number of Attributes:</strong> <em>8</em>
<strong>Date Donated:</strong> <em>1990-05-09</em>
<strong>Associated Tasks:</strong> <em>Classification</em>
<strong>Number of Web Hits:</strong> <em>352698</em>
<strong>Missing Values?</strong> <strong><em>Yes</em></strong></p>
<p>Source: Original Owners - National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases</p>
<p>Donor of database: Vincent Sigillito (vgs '@' aplcen.apl.jhu.edu), Research Center, RMI Group Leader, Applied Physics Laboratory, The Johns Hopkins University, Johns Hopkins Road, Laurel, MD 20707, (301) 953-6231</p>
<p>Data Set Information: Several constraints were placed on the selection of these instances from a larger database. In particular, all patients here are <strong>females at least 21 years old of Pima Indian heritage.</strong> ADAP is an adaptive learning routine that generates and executes digital analogs of perceptron-like devices. It is a unique algorithm; see the paper for details.</p>
<p><strong><em>Attribute Information:</em></strong></p>
<ol>
<li><strong>preg:</strong> Number of times pregnant </li>
<li><strong>plas:</strong> Plasma glucose concentration a 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test </li>
<li><strong>pres:</strong> Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg) </li>
<li><strong>skin:</strong> Triceps skin fold thickness (mm) </li>
<li><strong>test:</strong> 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml) </li>
<li><strong>mass:</strong> Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2) </li>
<li><strong>pedi:</strong> Diabetes pedigree function </li>
<li><strong>age:</strong> Age (years) </li>
<li><strong>class:</strong> Class variable (0 or 1) = False/True for onset of diabetes</li>
</ol>
<p>** UPDATE: Until 02/28/2011 this web page indicated that there were no missing values in the dataset. As pointed out by a repository user, this cannot be true: there are zeros in places where they are biologically impossible, such as the blood pressure attribute. It seems very likely that zero values encode missing data. However, since the dataset donors made no such statement we encourage you to use your best judgement and state your assumptions.</p>
<p>Relevant Papers: Smith, J.W., Everhart, J.E., Dickson, W.C., Knowler, W.C., & Johannes, R.S. (1988). Using the ADAP learning algorithm to forecast the onset of diabetes mellitus. In Proceedings of the Symposium on Computer Applications and Medical Care} (pp. 261--265). IEEE Computer Society Press. 
[Web Link]</p>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">read_csv</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span>
<span class="n">dataset</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'pima-indians-diabetes.csv'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">header</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># mark zero values as missing or NaN</span>
<span class="n">dataset</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">]]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">dataset</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">5</span><span class="p">]]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">replace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">numpy</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">NaN</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># print the first 20 rows of data</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">dataset</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">))</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Insights:">Insights:<a class="anchor-link" href="#Insights:">¶</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Pima-Indians-onset-of-diabetes-dataset-Prediction-using-Neural-Networks-in-Keras">Pima-Indians-onset-of-diabetes-dataset-Prediction-using-Neural-Networks-in-Keras<a class="anchor-link" href="#Pima-Indians-onset-of-diabetes-dataset-Prediction-using-Neural-Networks-in-Keras">¶</a></h2><p><a href="https://github.com/architsingh15/Pima-Indians-onset-of-diabetes-dataset-Prediction-using-Neural-Networks-in-Keras">https://github.com/architsingh15/Pima-Indians-onset-of-diabetes-dataset-Prediction-using-Neural-Networks-in-Keras</a></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [7]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">keras.models</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">Sequential</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">keras.layers</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">Dense</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">numpy</span>


<span class="n">numpy</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">random</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">seed</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span>


<span class="n">dataset</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">numpy</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loadtxt</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"pima-indians-diabetes.csv"</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">delimiter</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">","</span><span class="p">)</span>


<span class="n">Z</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">dataset</span><span class="p">[:,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">Q</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">dataset</span><span class="p">[:,</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">]</span>


<span class="n">model</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Sequential</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">add</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Dense</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">input_dim</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">activation</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'relu'</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">add</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Dense</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">activation</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'relu'</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">add</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Dense</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">activation</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'sigmoid'</span><span class="p">))</span>


<span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">compile</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">loss</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'binary_crossentropy'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">optimizer</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'adam'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">metrics</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'accuracy'</span><span class="p">])</span>


<span class="n">model</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Z</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Q</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">epochs</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">150</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">batch_size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span>
